03465nam a22005175i 9780822395270DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223952707 a10.1515/97808223952702doi  a(DE-B1597)552895  a(OCoLC)1167708013  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ759b.P27 2012 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a306.874/31 aParker, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Theorist's Mother /cAndrew Parker. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction Philosophy's Mother Trouble -- t1. Mom, Encore: Rereading, Teaching, and "Maternal Divination" -- t2. History, Fiction, and "The Author of Waverley"; or, Fathers and Sons in Marxist Criticism -- t3. Translating Revolution: Freud, Marx, and the Mameloshn -- tCoda: Other Maternities -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Theorist's Mother one of our subtlest literary theorists turns his attention to traces of the maternal in the lives and works of canonical male critical theorists. Noting how the mother is made to disappear both as the object of theory and as its subject, Andrew Parker focuses primarily on the legacies of Marx and Freud, who uniquely constrain their would-be heirs to "return to the origin" of each founding figure's texts. Analyzing the effects of these constraints in the work of Lukács, Lacan, and Derrida, among others, Parker suggests that the injunction to return transforms the history of theory into a form of genealogy, meaning that the mother must somehow be involved in this process, even if, as in Marxism, she seems wholly absent, or if her contributions are discounted, as in psychoanalysis. Far from being marginalized, the mother shows herself throughout this book to be inherently multiple and therefore never simply who or what theory may want her to be. In a provocative coda, Parker considers how theory's mother troubles will be affected retroactively by scientific advances that make it impossible to presume the mother's gender.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aMotherhoodxPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395270423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395270.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles